            queen, replacing the weaker Firzan (counselor).
          </p>
          <p>
            The bishop's movement expanded, and pawns could move two squares on their first move. These innovations made
            chess faster-paced and more dynamic. By the late 15th century, the rules were largely standardized, marking
            the birth of modern chess and its widespread popularity across Europe.
          </p>
